{"id":"gen-bio-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why is the small intestine so long and folded?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"The folds and villi massively increase the surface area, so more nutrients get absorbed in the same length of gut. It's the same trick as the alveoli in the lungs — whenever the body needs fast exchange it maximises surface area."}],"signals":{"windowSec":52,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":230,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Digestion","lessonSubject":"Biology","criticalConcepts":["surface area","absorption"]}
{"id":"gen-bio-flow-2","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"What is natural selection in one sentence?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"The individuals best suited to their environment survive and breed more, so their helpful traits become more common over generations. Give it enough time and the whole population shifts — that's how a species can change without anyone designing it."}],"signals":{"windowSec":55,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":255,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Evolution","lessonSubject":"Biology","criticalConcepts":["natural selection","variation"]}
{"id":"gen-bio-flow-3","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why do arteries have thick muscular walls?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Because blood leaves the heart under high pressure, so the walls need to be strong and elastic to take the surge and then recoil to keep it moving. Veins don't need that — lower pressure — so their walls are thinner and they use valves instead."}],"signals":{"windowSec":50,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":240,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Circulation","lessonSubject":"Biology","criticalConcepts":["arteries","blood pressure"]}
{"id":"gen-math-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Explain why a negative times a negative is a positive."},{"role":"pupil","content":"If multiplying by a negative flips the sign, then flipping twice gets you back to where you started, so it's positive. You can see it on a number line — each negative reverses direction, and two reversals point you forward again."}],"signals":{"windowSec":54,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":235,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Negative numbers","lessonSubject":"Maths","criticalConcepts":["sign rules"]}
{"id":"gen-math-flow-2","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"How do you find the area of a triangle and why does the formula work?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Half base times height. A triangle is exactly half of a rectangle with the same base and height, so you work out the rectangle's area and halve it. That's why it works for any triangle, not just right-angled ones."}],"signals":{"windowSec":56,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":245,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Area","lessonSubject":"Maths","criticalConcepts":["area of a triangle"]}
{"id":"gen-math-flow-3","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"What's the relationship between the mean and an outlier?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"An outlier drags the mean towards it because the mean uses every value. So if one number is way bigger, the mean gets pulled up even if most values are small. That's why the median is often fairer for skewed data."}],"signals":{"windowSec":53,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":230,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Averages","lessonSubject":"Maths","criticalConcepts":["mean","outliers"]}
{"id":"gen-eng-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why does the writer end the chapter on a question?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"It leaves the tension unresolved so you have to keep reading to get the answer. Ending on a question hands the suspense to the reader instead of closing it off — it's a cliffhanger built out of a single sentence."}],"signals":{"windowSec":51,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":225,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Structure","lessonSubject":"English","criticalConcepts":["cliffhanger","tension"]}
{"id":"gen-eng-flow-2","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"What's the effect of writing the whole poem in second person?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Saying 'you' pulls the reader straight into it, like it's happening to them and not some character. It makes it feel personal and a bit accusing, so you can't stay a neutral observer — the poem implicates you."}],"signals":{"windowSec":55,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":240,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Poetry","lessonSubject":"English","criticalConcepts":["second person","voice"]}
{"id":"gen-eng-flow-3","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"How does the metaphor 'the city was a furnace' work?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"It says the city is a furnace without 'like', so it's a metaphor not a simile, and it makes you feel the heat as something inescapable and man-made. A furnace is built to burn, so it hints the city itself is hostile, not just hot."}],"signals":{"windowSec":54,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":245,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Figurative language","lessonSubject":"English","criticalConcepts":["metaphor"]}
{"id":"gen-hist-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why was the Magna Carta important?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"It was the first time the king agreed in writing that he wasn't above the law, so even royals had limits. It didn't help ordinary people much then, but the idea that power has to follow rules became the foundation for later rights."}],"signals":{"windowSec":56,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":250,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Medieval England","lessonSubject":"History","criticalConcepts":["rule of law"]}
{"id":"gen-hist-flow-2","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why did the Roman army win so often?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"It was the organisation more than the soldiers — they drilled constantly, fought in tight formations, and built roads so they could move and resupply fast. A disciplined, well-supplied army beats a bigger disorganised one nearly every time."}],"signals":{"windowSec":55,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":250,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"The Romans","lessonSubject":"History","criticalConcepts":["military organisation"]}
{"id":"gen-hist-flow-3","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why did the slave trade last so long despite opposition?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Because too many people were profiting — plantation owners, traders, ports, banks all made money from it, so they fought to keep it. Moral arguments alone weren't enough until the economics and the campaigning both shifted."}],"signals":{"windowSec":57,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":240,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Transatlantic slavery","lessonSubject":"History","criticalConcepts":["economics","abolition"]}
